ak Shim'oni ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1986}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1987}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1988}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1989}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1990}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1991}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1992}}\n|[[Daniel Pe'er]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1993}}\n|Daniel Pe'er ||[[:he:\u05d3\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e8\u05d5\u05e4|Danny Rup]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1994}}\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|No commentator}} ||{{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1995}}\n|Daniel Pe'er ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1996}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}} ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|rowspan=\"20\" {{N/A|No commentator}} ||[[Yigal Ravid]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1999}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[:he:\u05d9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d1 \u05d2\u05d9\u05e0\u05d0\u05d9|Yoav Ginai]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2002}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[:he:\u05de\u05d9\u05db\u05dc \u05d6\u05d5\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5|Michal Zoharetz]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Merav Miller]] ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2005}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[:he:\u05d3\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05e8\u05de\u05df|Dana Herman]] ||{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/4422/dana_herman_to_give_israeli_televote/|title=Dana Herman to give Israeli televote|date=10 May 2005|accessdate=22 February 2020|work=ESCToday|first=Itamar|last=Barak}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2006}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n|[[Jason Danino-Holt]] ||{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/8275/former_mtv_europe_vj_to_present_israels_votes/|title=Former MTV Europe VJ to present Israel's votes|date=19 April 2007|accessdate=22 February 2020|work=ESCToday|first=Itamar|last=Barak}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|Noa Barak-Weshler ||\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n|rowspan=\"9\"|Ofer Nachshon ||{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\">{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/03/31/israel-lucy-ayoub-announced-as-eurovision-2018-spokesperson/|title=Israel: Lucy Ayoub Announced as Eurovision 2018 Spokesperson|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=22 February 2020|work=Eurovoix|first=Anthony|last=Granger}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n|{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n|Asaf Liberman and Shir Reuven {{small|(semi-final 1)}}<br>Itai Herman and Goel Pinto {{small|(semi-final 2)}}<br>[[Erez Tal]] and Idit Hershkowitz {{small|(final)}} ||[[Lucy Ayoub]] ||{{center|<ref name=\"ayoub\"/>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|Sharon Taicher and Eran Zarachowicz ||[[Izhar Cohen]] ||{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/04/15/israel-izhar-cohen-revealed-as-spokesperson/|title=Israel: Izhar Cohen Revealed as Spokesperson|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=22 February 2020|work=Eurovoix|first=Anthony|last=Granger}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n===Costume designers===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Year\n!Costume designers\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1979}}\n|dorin frankfurt\n|{{center|<ref>{{http://jpress.org.il/Olive/APA/NLI_heb/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=MAR%2F1979%2F03%2F15&id=Ar04200&sk=DBA814FF}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1983}}\n|dorin frankfurt\n|{{center|<ref>{{}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1985}}\n|nissim mizrachi\n|{{center|<ref>{{}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1988}}\n|Perach Reuven\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1991}}\n|Yaron Minkowsky\n|{{center|<ref>{{https://xnet.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4800758,00.html}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nimage:HallelujahEurovision1979.jpg|[[Milk and Honey (group)|Milk and Honey]], including [[Gali Atari]], in Jerusalem ({{Escyr|1979}})\nImage:David D'or.jpg|[[David D'Or]] in Istanbul ({{Escyr|2004}})\nImage:Teapacks Eurovision 2007.jpg|[[Teapacks]] in Helsinki ({{Escyr|2007}})\nImage:ESC 2008 - Israel - Boaz Mauda, 1st semifinal.jpg|[[Bo'az Ma'uda|Boaz]] in Belgrade ({{Escyr|2008}})\nimage:Harel Skaat - Milim (2nd Semi-final).jpg| [[Harel Skaat]] in Oslo ({{Escyr|2010}})\nimage:Dana Israel 2011.png|[[Dana International]] in D\u00fcsseldorf ({{Escyr|2011}})\nImage:ESC2013 - Israel 02 (crop).jpg|[[Moran Mazor]] in Malm\u00f6 ({{Escyr|2013}})\nImage:ESC2014 - Israel 01.jpg|[[Mei Finegold]] in Copenhagen ({{Escyr|2014}})\nImage:20150520 ESC 2015 Nadav Guedj 3542.jpg|[[Nadav Guedj]] in Vienna ({{Escyr|2015}})\nImage:ESC2016 - Israel 01.jpg|[[Hovi Star]] in Stockholm ({{Escyr|2016}})\nimage:Eurovision Song Contest 2017, Semi Final 2 Rehearsals. Photo 272.jpg|[[Imri Ziv|IMRI]] in Kyiv ({{Escyr|2017}})\nimage:ESC2018 - Israel 08.jpg|[[Netta Barzilai|Netta]]  in Lisbon ({{Escyr|2018}})\nimage:ESC2019-Israel.jpg|[[Kobi Marimi]] in Tel Aviv ({{Escyr|2019}})\n</gallery>\n\n== Arab reaction to Israeli participation ==\nIn [[Eurovision Song Contest 1978|1978]], during the performance of the Israeli entry, the [[Jordan]]ian broadcaster [[JRTV]] suspended the broadcast, and instead showed pictures of flowers. When it became apparent during the later stages of the voting sequence that Israel was going to win the contest, JRTV abruptly ended the transmission.<ref name=\"50yrs\">{{cite book|last = O'Connor|first = John Kennedy|year = 2005|title = The Eurovision Song Contest 50 Years The Official History|publisher=Carlton Books Limited|location = London|isbn = 1-84442-586-X}}</ref> Afterwards, the Jordanian news media refused to acknowledge the fact that Israel had won, and announced that the winner was Belgium (which had actually come in second).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=esctoday.com|year=2005|url=http://www.esctoday.com/annual/1978/participants.php|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1978|accessdate=8 May 2007}}</ref> By coincidence, Israel did not broadcast the victory either, as the IBA did not buy enough broadcasting time.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}} The victory was broadcast the next day.\n\nAt the time, Israeli Television was in its infancy and broadcasting in black & white. Many/most Israelis therefore watched international events in colour, using the signal from neighbouring Jordan. As Jordan did not broadcast the Israeli entry and the IBA did not broadcast the results part of the event, the win only became known as a result of radio broadcasts.\n\nBecause of Israel's participation in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], many [[Arab]] states that are eligible to participate do not do so. [[Tunisia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Tunisia]], [[Morocco in the Eurovision Song Contest|Morocco]], and [[Lebanon in the Eurovision Song Contest|Lebanon]] are cases in point.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for Morocco and Tunisia not participating due to Israel|date=October 2013}} Tunisia was about to participate in 1977, but decided not to do so in the end; Lebanon was just about to participate in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]] when it withdrew (incurring a fine by the EBU) because Lebanese law does not allow recognition of Israel, and consequently Lebanese television would not transmit any Israeli material \u2013 which would have been a violation of the EBU's rules.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[BBC News Online|BBC News]]|date=18 March 2005|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4362373.stm|title=Lebanon withdraws from Eurovision|accessdate=15 July 2006}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Music of Israel]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Israel in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits}}\n\n[[Category:Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n", "name_user": "Dummelaksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContestants", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest"}
{"title_page": "Rheumatology", "text_new": "{{for|the journal|Rheumatology (journal)}}\n{{Infobox medical specialty\n| title        = Rheumatology\n| subdivisions = \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| system       = [[Musculoskeletal system|Musculoskeletal]], [[Immune system|Immune]]\n| diseases     = [[Rheumatoid arthritis]], [[Systemic lupus erythematosus]], [[Osteoarthritis]], [[Psoriatic arthritis]], [[Ankylosing spondylitis]], [[Gout]], [[Osteoporosis]] \n| tests        = [[Arthrocentesis|Joint aspirate]], Musculoskeletal exam, [[X-ray]]\n| specialist   = Rheumatologist\n}}\n\n'''Rheumatology''' (Greek ''\u1fe5\u03b5\u1fe6\u03bc\u03b1'', ''rhe\u00fbma'', flowing current) is a branch of medicine devoted to the [[medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] and [[therapy]] of [[rheumatism|rheumatic diseases]]. [[Physician]]s who have undergone formal training in rheumatology are called '''rheumatologists'''. Rheumatologists deal mainly with immune-mediated disorders of the [[musculoskeletal system]], [[soft tissue]]s, [[autoimmune diseases]], [[vasculitis|vasculitides]], and heritable connective tissue disorders.\n\nMany of these diseases are now known to be disorders of the [[immune system]]. Rheumatology is considered to be the study and practice of [[immunology|medical immunology]].\n\nBeginning in the 2000s, the incorporation of drugs called the [[biologics]] (which include inhibitors of [[TNF-alpha]], certain [[interleukins]], and the [[JAK-STAT signaling pathway]]) into standards of care is one of the paramount developments in modern rheumatology.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Upchurch Katherine S., Kay Jonathan | year = 2012| title = Evolution of treatment for rheumatoid arthritis | url = | journal = Rheumatology | volume = 51| issue = suppl 6| pages = vi28\u2013vi36| doi = 10.1093/rheumatology/kes278 }}</ref>\n\n== Rheumatologist ==\n{{Infobox Occupation\n| name            = Rheumatologist\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| official_names  = Doctor, Medical Specialist\n<!------------Details------------------->\n| type= [[Specialty (medicine)|Specialty]]\n| activity_sector = [[Medicine]]\n| competencies    =\n| formation       =\n*[[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) \n* [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.)\n* [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] (MBBS/MBChB)\n| employment_field= [[Hospital]]s, [[Clinic]]s\n| related_occupation=\n}}\n\nA '''rheumatologist''' is a [[physician]] who specializes in the field of medical sub-specialty called rheumatology. A rheumatologist holds a board certification after specialized training after attaining a medical degree through fellowship programs in the United States, or specialist registrar positions in the United Kingdom, or DM in India or equivalent programs elsewhere in the world.  In the United States, training in this field requires four years undergraduate school, four years of medical school, and then three years of residency, followed by two or three years additional Fellowship training. The requirements may vary in other countries. Rheumatologists are [[internist]]s who are qualified by additional postgraduate training and experience in the diagnosis and treatment of arthritis and other diseases of the joints, muscles and bones. Many Rheumatologists also conduct research to determine the cause and better treatments for these disabling and sometimes fatal diseases. Treatment modalities are based on scientific research, currently, practice of rheumatology is largely evidence based.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rheumatology.org/Practice/Clinical/Patients/What_is_a_Rheumatologist_/|title=What is a Rheumatologist?|website=www.rheumatology.org}}</ref>\n\nRheumatologists treat [[arthritis]], [[autoimmune]] diseases, pain disorders affecting joints, and [[osteoporosis]]. There are more than 200 types of these diseases, including [[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[osteoarthritis]], [[gout]], [[Systemic lupus erythematosus|lupus]], back pain, [[osteoporosis]], and [[tendinitis]]. Some of these are very serious diseases that can be difficult to diagnose and treat. They treat soft tissue problems related to musculoskeletal system sports related soft tissue disorders.\n\n== Diseases ==\n{{Main|Rheumatism}}\nDiseases diagnosed or managed by rheumatologists include:\n\n=== Degenerative arthropathies ===\n* [[Osteoarthritis]]\n\n=== Inflammatory arthropathies ===\n* [[Rheumatoid arthritis]]\n* [[Spondyloarthropathy|Spondyloarthropathies]]\n**[[Ankylosing spondylitis]]\n**[[Reactive arthritis]] ([[reactive arthropathy]])\n**[[Psoriatic arthropathy]]\n**[[Enteropathic arthropathy]]\n* [[Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis]] (JIA)\n* Crystal arthropathies: [[gout]], [[pseudogout]]\n* [[Septic arthritis]]\n\n=== Systemic conditions and connective tissue diseases ===\n[[File:Laserbehandling.jpg|thumb|right|228px|Medical laser for the treatment of rheumatism.]]\n\n*[[Systemic Lupus Erythematosus|Lupus]]\n*[[Ehlers-Danlos syndrome]]\n*[[Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome]]\n*[[Scleroderma]] (systemic sclerosis)\n*[[Polymyositis]]\n*[[Dermatomyositis]]\n*[[Polymyalgia rheumatica]]\n*[[Mixed connective tissue disease]]\n*[[Relapsing polychondritis]]\n*[[Adult-onset Still's disease]]\n*[[Sarcoidosis]]\n*[[Fibromyalgia]]\n*[[Myofascial pain syndrome]]\n*[[Vasculitis]]\n** [[Microscopic polyangiitis]]\n** [[Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis]] (formerly known as Churg\u2013Strauss Syndrome)\n**[[Granulomatosis with polyangiitis]] (formerly known as Wegener's granulomatosis)\n** [[Polyarteritis nodosa]]\n**[[Henoch\u2013Sch\u00f6nlein purpura]]\n**[[Serum sickness]]\n**[[Giant cell arteritis]], [[Temporal arteritis]]\n**[[Takayasu's arteritis]]\n**[[Beh\u00e7et's syndrome]]\n**[[Kawasaki's disease]] (mucocutaneous lymph node syndrome)\n**[[Buerger's disease]] ([[thromboangiitis obliterans]])\n*[[Periodic fever syndrome|Hereditary periodic fever syndromes]]\n\n===Soft tissue rheumatism===\nLocal diseases and [[Lesion|lesions]] affecting the joints and structures around the joints including tendons, [[Ligament|ligaments]] capsules, [[Synovial bursa|bursae]], [[Stress fracture|stress fractures]], muscles, [[Nerve compression syndrome|nerve entrapment]], [[vascular lesions]], and [[Ganglion|ganglia]].  For example:\n*[[Low back pain]]\n*[[Tennis elbow]]\n*[[Golfer's elbow]]\n*[[Olecranon bursitis]]\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n\n===Physical examination===\nFollowing are examples of methods of diagnosis able to be performed in a normal physical examination.\n* [[Schober's test]] tests the flexion of the [[lower back]].\n* Multiple joint inspection\n* Musculoskeletal Examination\n** Screening Musculoskeletal Exam (SMSE) - a rapid assessment of structure and function\n** General Musculoskeletal Exam (GMSE) - a comprehensive assessment of joint inflammation\n** Regional Musculoskeletal Exam (RMSE) - focused assessments of structure, function and inflammation combined with special testing\n\n===Specialized===\n* [[Medical laboratory|Laboratory]] [[blood test|tests]] (e.g. [[Erythrocyte sedimentation rate|Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate]], [[Rheumatoid factor|Rheumatoid Factor]], Anti-CCP ([[Anti-citrullinated protein antibody]]), [[Anti-nuclear antibody|ANA (Anti-Nuclear Antibody)]] )\n* [[X-ray]]s, [[Ultrasound]]s, and other imaging methods of affected joints\n* [[Cytopathology]] and [[clinical chemistry|chemical pathology]] of fluid aspirated from affected joints (e.g. to differentiate between [[septic arthritis]] and [[gout]])\n\n== Treatment ==\nMost rheumatic diseases are treated with [[analgesic]]s, [[NSAID]]s (nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug), [[steroid]]s (in serious cases), [[DMARD]]s (disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs), [[monoclonal antibody|monoclonal antibodies]], such as  [[infliximab]] and [[adalimumab]], the [[TNF inhibitor]] [[etanercept]], and [[methotrexate]] for moderate to severe [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthritis.about.com/cs/mtx/a/mtx.htm |title=Methotrexate for rheumatoid arthritis |publisher=Arthritis.about.com |accessdate=2013-06-24}}</ref> The biologic agent [[rituximab]] (anti-B cell therapy) is now licensed for use in refractory rheumatoid arthritis.<ref>{{cite journal | display-authors = 4| author = Edwards J| author2 = Szczepanski L| author3 = Szechinski J| author4 = Filipowicz-Sosnowska A| author5 = Emery P| author6 = Close D| author7 = Stevens R| author8 = Shaw T | title = Efficacy of B-cell-targeted therapy with rituximab in patients with rheumatoid arthritis | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 350 | issue = 25 | pages = 2572\u20132581 | date = 2004 | pmid = 15201414 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa032534| url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/6967/}}</ref>\n[[Physiotherapy]] is vital in the treatment of many rheumatological disorders. [[Occupational therapy]] can help patients find alternative ways for common movements which would otherwise be restricted by their disease. Patients with rheumatoid arthritis often need a long term, coordinated and a multidisciplinary team approach towards management of individual patients. Treatment is often tailored according to the individual needs of each patient which is also dependent on the response and the tolerability of medications. \n\n===Rheumasurgery===\n''Rheumasurgery'' - sometimes called rheumatoid surgery - is a subfield of [[orthopedics]] occupied with the surgical treatment of patients with [[rheumatic diseases]].<ref>[http://tidsskriftet.no/article/1115480/ \"Norsk forening for revmakirurgi - Med hovedbase p\u00e5 Diakonhjemmet\"] LB Johannessen  Tidsskr Nor L\u00e6geforen 2004; 124:3110 Nr. 23 \u2013 2. December 2004</ref> The purpose of the interventions is to limit disease activity, soothe pain and improve function.<ref>[http://metodebok-ortopedi.ihelse.net/Metodebok_leger/rheumakirurgi.htm Rheumakirurgi]. Arne Skredderstuen November 2000</ref>\n\nRheumasurgical interventions can be divided in two groups. The one is early [[Synovectomy|synovectomies]], that is the removal of the inflamed [[synovia]] in order to prevent spreading and stop destruction. The other group is the so-called corrective intervention, i.e. an intervention done after destruction has taken place.<ref>Den sykehusmessige revmatikeromsorgen i Norge (K\u00e5ss and Stene 1970), page 24.</ref> Among the corrective interventions are joint replacements, removal of loose bone or cartilage fragments, and a variety of interventions aimed at repositioning and/or stabilizing joints,<ref>[http://www.cedars-sinai.edu/Patients/Programs-and-Services/Rheumatology/Treatments/Surgery-for-Rheumatic-Diseases.aspx \"Surgery for Rheumatic Diseases\"] Cedars Sinai (http://www.cedars-sinai.edu)</ref> such as [[arthrodesis]].\n\n== Research directions ==\nRecently, a large body of scientific research deals with the background of [[autoimmune disease]], the cause of many rheumatic disorders. Also, the field of [[osteoimmunology]] has emerged to further examine the interactions between the immune system, joints and bones. Epidemiological studies and medication trials are also being conducted. Scientific research on biologics and clinical trials on monoclonal antibody therapies have added a new dimension to the medical treatment of arthritic disorders.{{cn|date=November 2017}} The [[Rheumatology Research Foundation]] is the largest private funding source of rheumatology research and training in the United States.\n\n==History==\n\nRheumasurgery emerged in the cooperation of rheumatologists and orthopedic surgeons in [[Heinola]], Finland, during the 1950s.<ref>Revmatisme: Gamle plager - ny viten (Munthe and Larsen 1987), page 49.</ref>\n\nIn 1970 a Norwegian investigation estimated that at least 50% of patients with rheumatic symptoms needed rheumasurgery as an integrated part of their treatment.<ref>Den sykehusmessige revmatikeromsorgen i Norge (K\u00e5ss and Stene 1970), pages 24-25.</ref>\n\n[[The European Rheumatoid Arthritis Surgical Society]] (ERASS) was founded in 1979.<ref>Rydholm, U \"[http://docplayer.se/3804218-Nar-jag-borjade-min-tjanstgoring.html Reumakirurgiens uppg\u00e5ng, stabilisering og nedg\u00e5ng ur ett sydsvenskt perspektiv\"] 2013</ref>\n\nAround the turn of the century, focus for treatment of patients with rheumatic disease shifted, and pharmacological treatment became dominant, while surgical interventions became rarer.<ref>[http://www.mediahuset.se/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/NRB-4_12_web.pdf Trender i revmakirurgisk behandling av pasienter med leddgikt og andre kronisk inflammatoriske leddsykdommer], Norsk Rheumabulletin 4/2012, pages 16-17.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Nikiphorou E, Carpenter L, Morris S | display-authors = etal | year = 2014 | title = Hand and foot surgery rates in rheumatoid arthritis have declined from 1986 to 2011, but large-joint replacement rates remain unchanged: results from two UK inception cohorts | url = | journal = Arthritis Rheumatol | volume = 66 | issue = 5| pages = 1081\u20139 | doi = 10.1002/art.38344 | pmid = 24782174 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rhumatologie.org Association des medecins rhumatologues du Quebec]\n* [http://www.rheumatology.org American College of Rheumatology]\n* [http://www.eular.org European League Against Rheumatism]\n* [http://www.corrona.org/ Consortium of Rheumatology Researchers of North America, Inc.]\n* [http://www.rheumatology.org.uk/ British Society for Rheumatology]\n* [http://www.rheum.ca/en/ Canadian Rheumatology Association]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090303110442/http://www.rheumatology.org/arhp/ Association of Rheumatology Health Professionals]\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Rheumatology|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the journal|Rheumatology (journal)}}\n{{Infobox medical specialty\n| title        = Rheumatology\n| subdivisions = \n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| system       = [[Musculoskeletal system|Musculoskeletal]], [[Immune system|Immune]]\n| diseases     = [[Rheumatoid arthritis]], [[Systemic lupus erythematosus]], [[Osteoarthritis]], [[Psoriatic arthritis]], [[Ankylosing spondylitis]], [[Gout]], [[Osteoporosis]] \n| tests        = [[Arthrocentesis|Joint aspirate]], Musculoskeletal exam, [[X-ray]]\n| specialist   = Rheumatologist\n}}\n\n'''Rheumatology''' (Greek ''\u1fe5\u03b5\u1fe6\u03bc\u03b1'', ''rhe\u00fbma'', flowing current) is a branch of medicine devoted to the [[medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] and [[therapy]] of [[rheumatism|rheumatic diseases]]. [[Physician]]s who have undergone formal training in rheumatology are called '''rheumatologists'''. Rheumatologists deal mainly with immune-mediated disorders of the [[musculoskeletal system]], [[soft tissue]]s, [[autoimmune diseases]], [[vasculitis|vasculitides]], and heritable connective tissue disorders.\n\nMany of these diseases are now known to be disorders of the [[immune system]]. Rheumatology is considered to be the study and practice of [[immunology|medical immunology]].\n\nBeginning in the 2000s, the incorporation of drugs called the [[biologics]] (which include inhibitors of [[TNF-alpha]], certain [[interleukins]], and the [[JAK-STAT signaling pathway]]) into standards of care is one of the paramount developments in modern rheumatology.<ref>Katherine S. Upchurch, Jonathan Kay. \"Evolution of treatment for rheumatoid arthritis\". ''Rheumatology'' (Oxford). 2012 Dec;51 Suppl 6:vi28-vi36. {{doi|10.1093/rheumatology/kes278}}.</ref>\n\n== Rheumatologist ==\n{{Infobox Occupation\n| name            = Rheumatologist\n| image           =\n| caption         =\n| official_names  = Doctor, Medical Specialist\n<!------------Details------------------->\n| type= [[Specialty (medicine)|Specialty]]\n| activity_sector = [[Medicine]]\n| competencies    =\n| formation       =\n*[[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) \n* [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.)\n* [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] (MBBS/MBChB)\n| employment_field= [[Hospital]]s, [[Clinic]]s\n| related_occupation=\n}}\n\nA '''rheumatologist''' is a [[physician]] who specializes in the field of medical sub-specialty called rheumatology. A rheumatologist holds a board certification after specialized training after attaining a medical degree through fellowship programs in the United States, or specialist registrar positions in the United Kingdom, or DM in India or equivalent programs elsewhere in the world.  In the United States, training in this field requires four years undergraduate school, four years of medical school, and then three years of residency, followed by two or three years additional Fellowship training. The requirements may vary in other countries. Rheumatologists are [[internist]]s who are qualified by additional postgraduate training and experience in the diagnosis and treatment of arthritis and other diseases of the joints, muscles and bones. Many Rheumatologists also conduct research to determine the cause and better treatments for these disabling and sometimes fatal diseases. Treatment modalities are based on scientific research, currently, practice of rheumatology is largely evidence based.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rheumatology.org/Practice/Clinical/Patients/What_is_a_Rheumatologist_/|title=What is a Rheumatologist?|website=www.rheumatology.org}}</ref>\n\nRheumatologists treat [[arthritis]], [[autoimmune]] diseases, pain disorders affecting joints, and [[osteoporosis]]. There are more than 200 types of these diseases, including [[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[osteoarthritis]], [[gout]], [[Systemic lupus erythematosus|lupus]], back pain, [[osteoporosis]], and [[tendinitis]]. Some of these are very serious diseases that can be difficult to diagnose and treat. They treat soft tissue problems related to musculoskeletal system sports related soft tissue disorders.\n\n== Diseases ==\n{{Main|Rheumatism}}\nDiseases diagnosed or managed by rheumatologists include:\n\n=== Degenerative arthropathies ===\n* [[Osteoarthritis]]\n\n=== Inflammatory arthropathies ===\n* [[Rheumatoid arthritis]]\n* [[Spondyloarthropathy|Spondyloarthropathies]]\n**[[Ankylosing spondylitis]]\n**[[Reactive arthritis]] ([[reactive arthropathy]])\n**[[Psoriatic arthropathy]]\n**[[Enteropathic arthropathy]]\n* [[Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis]] (JIA)\n* Crystal arthropathies: [[gout]], [[pseudogout]]\n* [[Septic arthritis]]\n\n=== Systemic conditions and connective tissue diseases ===\n[[File:Laserbehandling.jpg|thumb|right|228px|Medical laser for the treatment of rheumatism.]]\n\n*[[Systemic Lupus Erythematosus|Lupus]]\n*[[Ehlers-Danlos syndrome]]\n*[[Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome]]\n*[[Scleroderma]] (systemic sclerosis)\n*[[Polymyositis]]\n*[[Dermatomyositis]]\n*[[Polymyalgia rheumatica]]\n*[[Mixed connective tissue disease]]\n*[[Relapsing polychondritis]]\n*[[Adult-onset Still's disease]]\n*[[Sarcoidosis]]\n*[[Fibromyalgia]]\n*[[Myofascial pain syndrome]]\n*[[Vasculitis]]\n** [[Microscopic polyangiitis]]\n** [[Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis]] (formerly known as Churg\u2013Strauss Syndrome)\n**[[Granulomatosis with polyangiitis]] (formerly known as Wegener's granulomatosis)\n** [[Polyarteritis nodosa]]\n**[[Henoch\u2013Sch\u00f6nlein purpura]]\n**[[Serum sickness]]\n**[[Giant cell arteritis]], [[Temporal arteritis]]\n**[[Takayasu's arteritis]]\n**[[Beh\u00e7et's syndrome]]\n**[[Kawasaki's disease]] (mucocutaneous lymph node syndrome)\n**[[Buerger's disease]] ([[thromboangiitis obliterans]])\n*[[Periodic fever syndrome|Hereditary periodic fever syndromes]]\n\n===Soft tissue rheumatism===\nLocal diseases and [[Lesion|lesions]] affecting the joints and structures around the joints including tendons, [[Ligament|ligaments]] capsules, [[Synovial bursa|bursae]], [[Stress fracture|stress fractures]], muscles, [[Nerve compression syndrome|nerve entrapment]], [[vascular lesions]], and [[Ganglion|ganglia]].  For example:\n*[[Low back pain]]\n*[[Tennis elbow]]\n*[[Golfer's elbow]]\n*[[Olecranon bursitis]]\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n\n===Physical examination===\nFollowing are examples of methods of diagnosis able to be performed in a normal physical examination.\n* [[Schober's test]] tests the flexion of the [[lower back]].\n* Multiple joint inspection\n* Musculoskeletal Examination\n** Screening Musculoskeletal Exam (SMSE) - a rapid assessment of structure and function\n** General Musculoskeletal Exam (GMSE) - a comprehensive assessment of joint inflammation\n** Regional Musculoskeletal Exam (RMSE) - focused assessments of structure, function and inflammation combined with special testing\n\n===Specialized===\n* [[Medical laboratory|Laboratory]] [[blood test|tests]] (e.g. [[Erythrocyte sedimentation rate|Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate]], [[Rheumatoid factor|Rheumatoid Factor]], Anti-CCP ([[Anti-citrullinated protein antibody]]), [[Anti-nuclear antibody|ANA (Anti-Nuclear Antibody)]] )\n* [[X-ray]]s, [[Ultrasound]]s, and other imaging methods of affected joints\n* [[Cytopathology]] and [[clinical chemistry|chemical pathology]] of fluid aspirated from affected joints (e.g. to differentiate between [[septic arthritis]] and [[gout]])\n\n== Treatment ==\nMost rheumatic diseases are treated with [[analgesic]]s, [[NSAID]]s (nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug), [[steroid]]s (in serious cases), [[DMARD]]s (disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs), [[monoclonal antibody|monoclonal antibodies]], such as  [[infliximab]] and [[adalimumab]], the [[TNF inhibitor]] [[etanercept]], and [[methotrexate]] for moderate to severe [[rheumatoid arthritis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthritis.about.com/cs/mtx/a/mtx.htm |title=Methotrexate for rheumatoid arthritis |publisher=Arthritis.about.com |accessdate=2013-06-24}}</ref> The biologic agent [[rituximab]] (anti-B cell therapy) is now licensed for use in refractory rheumatoid arthritis.<ref>{{cite journal | display-authors = 4| author = Edwards J| author2 = Szczepanski L| author3 = Szechinski J| author4 = Filipowicz-Sosnowska A| author5 = Emery P| author6 = Close D| author7 = Stevens R| author8 = Shaw T | title = Efficacy of B-cell-targeted therapy with rituximab in patients with rheumatoid arthritis | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 350 | issue = 25 | pages = 2572\u20132581 | date = 2004 | pmid = 15201414 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa032534| url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/6967/}}</ref>\n[[Physiotherapy]] is vital in the treatment of many rheumatological disorders. [[Occupational therapy]] can help patients find alternative ways for common movements which would otherwise be restricted by their disease. Patients with rheumatoid arthritis often need a long term, coordinated and a multidisciplinary team approach towards management of individual patients. Treatment is often tailored according to the individual needs of each patient which is also dependent on the response and the tolerability of medications. \n\n===Rheumasurgery===\n''Rheumasurgery'' - sometimes called rheumatoid surgery - is a subfield of [[orthopedics]] occupied with the surgical treatment of patients with [[rheumatic diseases]].<ref>[http://tidsskriftet.no/article/1115480/ \"Norsk forening for revmakirurgi - Med hovedbase p\u00e5 Diakonhjemmet\"] LB Johannessen  Tidsskr Nor L\u00e6geforen 2004; 124:3110 Nr. 23 \u2013 2. December 2004</ref> The purpose of the interventions is to limit disease activity, soothe pain and improve function.<ref>[http://metodebok-ortopedi.ihelse.net/Metodebok_leger/rheumakirurgi.htm Rheumakirurgi]. Arne Skredderstuen November 2000</ref>\n\nRheumasurgical interventions can be divided in two groups. The one is early [[Synovectomy|synovectomies]], that is the removal of the inflamed [[synovia]] in order to prevent spreading and stop destruction. The other group is the so-called corrective intervention, i.e. an intervention done after destruction has taken place.<ref>Den sykehusmessige revmatikeromsorgen i Norge (K\u00e5ss and Stene 1970), page 24.</ref> Among the corrective interventions are joint replacements, removal of loose bone or cartilage fragments, and a variety of interventions aimed at repositioning and/or stabilizing joints,<ref>[http://www.cedars-sinai.edu/Patients/Programs-and-Services/Rheumatology/Treatments/Surgery-for-Rheumatic-Diseases.aspx \"Surgery for Rheumatic Diseases\"] Cedars Sinai (http://www.cedars-sinai.edu)</ref> such as [[arthrodesis]].\n\n== Research directions ==\nRecently, a large body of scientific research deals with the background of [[autoimmune disease]], the cause of many rheumatic disorders. Also, the field of [[osteoimmunology]] has emerged to further examine the interactions between the immune system, joints and bones. Epidemiological studies and medication trials are also being conducted. Scientific research on biologics and clinical trials on monoclonal antibody therapies have added a new dimension to the medical treatment of arthritic disorders.{{cn|date=November 2017}} The [[Rheumatology Research Foundation]] is the largest private funding source of rheumatology research and training in the United States.\n\n==History==\n\nRheumasurgery emerged in the cooperation of rheumatologists and orthopedic surgeons in [[Heinola]], Finland, during the 1950s.<ref>Revmatisme: Gamle plager - ny viten (Munthe and Larsen 1987), page 49.</ref>\n\nIn 1970 a Norwegian investigation estimated that at least 50% of patients with rheumatic symptoms needed rheumasurgery as an integrated part of their treatment.<ref>Den sykehusmessige revmatikeromsorgen i Norge (K\u00e5ss and Stene 1970), pages 24-25.</ref>\n\n[[The European Rheumatoid Arthritis Surgical Society]] (ERASS) was founded in 1979.<ref>Rydholm, U \"[http://docplayer.se/3804218-Nar-jag-borjade-min-tjanstgoring.html Reumakirurgiens uppg\u00e5ng, stabilisering og nedg\u00e5ng ur ett sydsvenskt perspektiv\"] 2013</ref>\n\nAround the turn of the century, focus for treatment of patients with rheumatic disease shifted, and pharmacological treatment became dominant, while surgical interventions became rarer.<ref>[http://www.mediahuset.se/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/NRB-4_12_web.pdf Trender i revmakirurgisk behandling av pasienter med leddgikt og andre kronisk inflammatoriske leddsykdommer], Norsk Rheumabulletin 4/2012, pages 16-17.</ref><ref>Nikiphorou E, Carpenter L, Morris S, et al. \"Hand and foot surgery rates in rheumatoid arthritis have declined from 1986 to 2011, but large-joint replacement rates remain unchanged: results from two UK inception cohorts.\" ''Arthritis Rheumatol''. 2014;66(5):1081-9. {{doi|10.1002/art.38344}}. {{PMID|24782174}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rhumatologie.org Association des medecins rhumatologues du Quebec]\n* [http://www.rheumatology.org American College of Rheumatology]\n* [http://www.eular.org European League Against Rheumatism]\n* [http://www.corrona.org/ Consortium of Rheumatology Researchers of North America, Inc.]\n* [http://www.rheumatology.org.uk/ British Society for Rheumatology]\n* [http://www.rheum.ca/en/ Canadian Rheumatology Association]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090303110442/http://www.rheumatology.org/arhp/ Association of Rheumatology Health Professionals]\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Rheumatology|*]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites (Diberri fmt authors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rheumatology"}
{"title_page": "Bamum language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language \n|name=Bamum\n|nativename=''Sh\u00fcpamom''\n|region= [[Cameroon]], [[Nigeria]]\n|ethnicity=[[Bamum people]]\n|speakers=420,000 \n|date=2005\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Benue\u2013Congo]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Bantoid]]\n|fam5=[[Grassfields languages|Grassfields]]\n|fam6=[[Eastern Grassfields languages|Eastern Grassfields (Mbam\u2013Nkam)]]\n|fam7=[[Nun languages|Nun]]\n|script=Latin script, [[Bamum script|Bamum syllabary]] (being revived)\n|map=Shumom-text.jpg\n|mapcaption=Page from a manuscript in the [[Bamum script]]\n|iso3=bax\n|glotto=bamu1253\n|glottorefname=Bamun\n}}\n\n'''Bamum''' (''Sh\u00fc Pamom'' {{IPA-xx|\u0283\u0177p\u01ce\u02d1m\u0259\u0300m|}} \"language of the Bamum\", or ''Sh\u00fcmom'' \"Mum language\"), also spelled '''Bamun''' or in its [[French language|French]] spelling '''Bamoun''', is an [[Eastern Grassfields language]] of [[Cameroon]], with approximately 420,000 speakers.<ref name=\"e18\"/> The language is well known for its [[Bamum script|original script]] developed by [[Ibrahim Njoya|King Njoya]] and his palace circle around 1895. Cameroonian musician [[Claude Ndam]] is a native speaker of the language and uses it in his music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200509140606.html|title=Cameroon: Claude Ndam : Committed To Culture|author=Cathy Kell|date=14 September 2005|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\nBamum has [[Tone (linguistics)|tone]], vowel length, diphthongs and [[syllable coda|coda]] consonants.\n\n=== Vowels ===\nThe simple vowels are:\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Front!!Central!! colspan=\"2\" |Back\n|-align=\"center\"\n!\n!Unrounded\n!Rounded\n!Unrounded\n!Unrounded\n!Rounded\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Close</big>'''\n| align=\"center\" |i\n|y|| align=\"center\" |\u0268 || align=\"right\" |\u026f\n|u\n|- align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Mid</big>'''\n| e\n| || \u0259||\n|\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Open-mid</big>'''\n| align=\"center\" | \u025b\n| ||  || align=\"center\" |\n|\u0254\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Open</big>'''\n| \n| || a ||\n|\n|}\nBamum vowels can be normal or half-long /\u02d1/.\n\n=== Consonants===\nThe consonants are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|-\n!\n!\n!\n!Labial!!Alveolar!!Post-<br>alveolar/<br>Palatal!!Velar!!Labialized<br>velar!!Labial-<br>velar!!Glottal\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Plosive\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Plain\n|Voiceless\n|p||t|| ||k||k\u02b7||k\u0361p||\u0294\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|b||d|| ||\u0261||\u0261\u02b7||g\u0361b||\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Prenasalized\n|Voiceless\n|\u1d50p||\u207ft||  ||\u1d51k||\u1d51k\u02b7||\u1d51\u0361\u1d50k\u0361p||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|\u1d50b||\u207fd||  ||\u1d51\u0261||\u1d51\u0261\u02b7\n|\u1d51\u0361\u1d50g\u0361b\n|\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Fricative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Plain\n|Voiceless\n|f||s||\u0283||x||x\u02b7||  ||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|v||z||\u0292||\u0263||\u0263\u02b7||  ||\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Prenasalized\n|Voiceless\n|\u1dacf||\u207fs||\u1dae\u0283||  || || ||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|\u1dacv||\u207fz||\u1dae\u0292||  || || ||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Nasal\n|m||n||\u0272||\u014b||\u014b\u02b7||\u014b\u0361m||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Rhotic\n| ||r||\u0279\u0320|| || || ||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Approximant\n| ||l|| || ||w|| ||\n|}\n\n=== Tones ===\n\nBamum has five tones<ref>https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2007/07023-bamum-report.pdf</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Tone !! IPA\n|-\n| \u00e0 || low\n|-\n| \u00e1 || mid\n|-\n| \u0101 || high\n|-\n| \u01ce || rising\n|-\n| \u00e2 || falling\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Languages of Cameroon}}\n{{Languages of Nigeria}}\n{{Grassfields Bantu languages}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bamum language}}\n[[Category:Languages of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Languages of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nun languages]]\n\n\n{{Cameroon-lang-stub}}\n{{gras-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language \n|name=Bamum\n|nativename=Sh\u00fcpamom\n|region= [[Cameroon]], [[Nigeria]]\n|ethnicity=[[Bamum people]]\n|speakers=420,000 \n|date=2005\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Benue\u2013Congo]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Bantoid]]\n|fam5=[[Grassfields languages|Grassfields]]\n|fam6=[[Eastern Grassfields languages|Eastern Grassfields (Mbam\u2013Nkam)]]\n|fam7=[[Nun languages|Nun]]\n|script=Latin script, [[Bamum script|Bamum syllabary]] (being revived)\n|map=Shumom-text.jpg\n|mapcaption=Page from a manuscript in the [[Bamum script]]\n|iso3=bax\n|glotto=bamu1253\n|glottorefname=Bamun\n}}\n\n'''Bamum''' (''Sh\u00fc Pamom'' {{IPA-xx|\u0283\u0177p\u01ce\u02d1m\u0259\u0300m|}} \"language of the Bamum\", or ''Sh\u00fcmom'' \"Mum language\"), also spelled '''Bamun''' or in its [[French language|French]] spelling '''Bamoun''', is an [[Eastern Grassfields language]] of [[Cameroon]], with approximately 420,000 speakers.<ref name=\"e18\"/> The language is well known for its [[Bamum script|original script]] developed by [[Ibrahim Njoya|King Njoya]] and his palace circle around 1895. Cameroonian musician [[Claude Ndam]] is a native speaker of the language and uses it in his music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200509140606.html|title=Cameroon: Claude Ndam : Committed To Culture|author=Cathy Kell|date=14 September 2005|accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\nBamum has [[Tone (linguistics)|tone]], vowel length, diphthongs and [[syllable coda|coda]] consonants.\n\n=== Vowels ===\nThe simple vowels are:\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Front!!Central!! colspan=\"2\" |Back\n|-align=\"center\"\n!\n!Unrounded\n!Rounded\n!Unrounded\n!Unrounded\n!Rounded\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Close</big>'''\n| align=\"center\" |i\n|y|| align=\"center\" |\u0268 || align=\"right\" |\u026f\n|u\n|- align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Mid</big>'''\n| e\n| || \u0259||\n|\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Open-mid</big>'''\n| align=\"center\" | \u025b\n| ||  || align=\"center\" |\n|\u0254\n|-align=\"center\"\n|'''<big>Open</big>'''\n| \n| || a ||\n|\n|}\nBamum vowels can be normal or half-long /\u02d1/.\n\n=== Consonants===\nThe consonants are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable IPA\"\n|-\n!\n!\n!\n!Labial!!Alveolar!!Post-<br>alveolar/<br>Palatal!!Velar!!Labialized<br>velar!!Labial-<br>velar!!Glottal\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Plosive\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Plain\n|Voiceless\n|p||t|| ||k||k\u02b7||k\u0361p||\u0294\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|b||d|| ||\u0261||\u0261\u02b7||g\u0361b||\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Prenasalized\n|Voiceless\n|\u1d50p||\u207ft||  ||\u1d51k||\u1d51k\u02b7||\u1d51\u0361\u1d50k\u0361p||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|\u1d50b||\u207fd||  ||\u1d51\u0261||\u1d51\u0261\u02b7\n|\u1d51\u0361\u1d50g\u0361b\n|\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Fricative\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Plain\n|Voiceless\n|f||s||\u0283||x||x\u02b7||  ||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|v||z||\u0292||\u0263||\u0263\u02b7||  ||\n|-align=center\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Prenasalized\n|Voiceless\n|\u1dacf||\u207fs||\u1dae\u0283||  || || ||\n|-align=center\n|Voiced\n|\u1dacv||\u207fz||\u1dae\u0292||  || || ||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Nasal\n|m||n||\u0272||\u014b||\u014b\u02b7||\u014b\u0361m||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Rhotic\n| ||r||\u0279\u0320|| || || ||\n|-align=center\n| colspan=\"3\" |Approximant\n| ||l|| || ||w|| ||\n|}\n\n=== Tones ===\n\nBamum has five tones<ref>https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2007/07023-bamum-report.pdf</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Tone !! IPA\n|-\n| \u00e0 || low\n|-\n| \u00e1 || mid\n|-\n| \u0101 || high\n|-\n| \u01ce || rising\n|-\n| \u00e2 || falling\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Languages of Cameroon}}\n{{Languages of Nigeria}}\n{{Grassfields Bantu languages}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bamum language}}\n[[Category:Languages of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Languages of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nun lan